04829nam a22005775i 9780804778169DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047781697 a10.1515/97808047781692doi  a(DE-B1597)564013  a(OCoLC)1198931826  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD8728 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a331.4089a331.4089/99210521351 aParreñas, Rhacel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIllicit Flirtations :bLabor, Migration, and Sex Trafficking in Tokyo /cRhacel Parreñas. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction. THE INDENTUR ED MOBILITY OF MIGR ANT HOSTESSES -- tChapter One. THE MIGRATION OF ENTERTAINERS TO JAPAN -- tChapter Two. THE LABOR SYSTEM IN HOSTESS CLUBS -- tChapter Three. BUTTRESSING MASCULINITY -- tChapter Four. THE RISKY BUSINESS OF LOVE -- tChapter Five. CULTURES OF FLIRTATION -- tChapter Six. MAKING LOVE FOR A VISA -- tChapter Seven. THE INVI S IBILITY OF HOSTESSES -- tChapter Eight. THE SEGREGATION OF HOSTESSES -- tConclusion. ENSURING THE SAFE PASSAGE OF MIGRANT HOSTESSES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2004, the U.S. State Department declared Filipina hostesses in Japan the largest group of sex trafficked persons in the world. Since receiving this global attention, the number of hostesses entering Japan has dropped by nearly 90 percent-from more than 80,000 in 2004 to just over 8,000 today. To some, this might suggest a victory for the global anti-trafficking campaign, but Rhacel Parreñas counters that this drastic decline-which stripped thousands of migrants of their livelihoods-is in truth a setback. Parreñas worked alongside hostesses in a working-class club in Tokyo's red-light district, serving drinks, singing karaoke, and entertaining her customers, including members of the yakuza, the Japanese crime syndicate. While the common assumption has been that these hostess bars are hotbeds of sexual trafficking, Parreñas quickly discovered a different world of working migrant women, there by choice, and, most importantly, where none were coerced into prostitution. But this is not to say that the hostesses were not vulnerable in other ways. Illicit Flirtations challenges our understandings of human trafficking and calls into question the U.S. policy to broadly label these women as sex trafficked. It highlights how in imposing top-down legal constraints to solve the perceived problems-including laws that push dependence on migrant brokers, guest worker policies that bind migrants to an employer, marriage laws that limit the integration of migrants, and measures that criminalize undocumented migrants-many women become more vulnerable to exploitation, not less. It is not the jobs themselves, but the regulation that makes migrants susceptible to trafficking. If we are to end the exploitation of people, we first need to understand the actual experiences of migrants, not rest on global policy statements. This book gives a long overdue look into the real world of those labeled as trafficked.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aForeign workers, FilipinoxJapanxTokyo. 0aForeign workers, FilipinozJapanzTokyo. 0aHostess clubsxJapanxTokyo. 0aHostess clubszJapanzTokyo. 0aHuman traffickingxJapanxTokyo. 0aHuman traffickingzJapanzTokyo. 0aWomen foreign workersxJapanxTokyo. 0aWomen foreign workerszJapanzTokyo. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978